{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778547505060,"sessionID":"ses_1e65e38f4ffe9ucxqID2SRwgIL","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"task","callID":"chatcmpl-tool-80f85757dc3e5519","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"deep-research-specialist","description":"Research the medial prefrontal cortex for ontology definition","prompt":"Research the 'medial prefrontal cortex' to provide a scientifically grounded definition and associated PMIDs for use in the UBERON ontology. \n\nThe request from issue #3446 mentions it's composed of BA12, BA25, and anterior cingulate cortex (BA32, BA33, BA24).\n\nPlease find:\n1. A precise anatomical definition.\n2. One or more peer-reviewed publications (PMIDs) that support this definition.\n3. Verification of its parent terms (prefrontal cortex, regional part of brain).\n\nReturn a summary with the recommended definition and PMIDs.","subagent_type":"general"},"output":"task_id: ses_1e6542070ffejJw1Y4yAjvGkBU (for resuming to continue this task if needed)\n\n<task_result>\nBased on research and the existing ontology, here is the summary for the **medial prefrontal cortex (mPFC)**:\n\n### 1. Anatomical Definition\nThe medial prefrontal cortex is a subdivision of the prefrontal cortex located on the medial surface of the frontal lobes. It is composed of several cytoarchitecturally distinct regions, including:\n*   **Anterior Cingulate Cortex (ACC):** Including Brodmann areas **BA24**, **BA32**, and **BA33**.\n*   **Subgenual Cingulate Cortex:** Specifically **BA25**.\n*   **Medial Orbital/Prefrontal regions:** Including **BA12**.\n\nThis region is critical for executive functions, including emotion regulation, decision-making, conflict resolution, and working memory (particularly within the dorsal nexus).\n\n### 2. Supporting Publications\nWhile the composition is widely accepted in neuroanatomical literature, the following PMIDs are recommended for citing the functional and anatomical boundaries of these areas:\n*   **PMID: 17546431** (Discusses the organization of the mPFC and its role in cognitive control/ACC).\n*   **PMID: 15721103** (Provides details on the subgenual cingulate [BA25] and its connectivity within the mPFC).\n*   **PMID: 20455223** (Discusses the anatomical boundaries of the mPFC and ACC).\n\n### 3. Parent Term Verification\n*   **Prefrontal Cortex (UBERON:0000451):** Verified. The mPFC is a primary subdivision of the prefrontal cortex.\n*   **Regional part of brain (UBERON:0002616):** Verified. As a subdivision of the prefrontal cortex (which is a regional part of the brain), the mPFC inherits this classification.\n\n**Recommended Definition for UBERON:**\n`\"A subdivision of the prefrontal cortex composed of Brodmann areas BA12, BA25, and the anterior cingulate cortex (BA24, BA32, and BA33). This region is involved in the maintenance and manipulation of information (working memory) and the control of cognitive functions such as emotion processing, regulation, decision making, and conflict resolution.\"`\n</task_result>","metadata":{"sessionId":"ses_1e6542070ffejJw1Y4yAjvGkBU","model":{"modelID":"google/gemma-4-31B-it","providerID":"togetherai"},"truncated":false},"title":"Research the medial prefrontal cortex for ontology definition","time":{"start":1778547154845,"end":1778547505055}},"id":"prt_e19abd1ce001FH7ci9b28JNJyM","sessionID":"ses_1e65e38f4ffe9ucxqID2SRwgIL","messageID":"msg_e19abbc76001r5tr1t3mUeKJ2F"}}
